h. Similar strengths and weaknesses to P2, with the added glycol recovery step. Marginal improvement in convergence but same core limitations: formamidine formation and missing formaldehyde source specification.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Cross-link to formaldehyde source explicitly\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"Alternative ethanol oxidation branch avoids formamidine but introduces the critical oxidation problem. rxn_009 (erythrose + CH\u2082O + NH\u2083 \u2192 imidazole-4-ethanol) is experimentally demonstrated by Shen et al. at 5.4% yield, which is actually higher than the direct aldehyde route. However, rxn_011 (ethanol \u2192 aldehyde oxidation) has no clearly identified prebiotic oxidant. Shen et al. speculate about ferric iron, sulfur, or aldehyde oxidants but provide no experimental validation. This is a significant gap flagged explicitly in the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify candidate oxidant explicitly: ferric iron on pyrite surfaces, MnO\u2082, or photooxidation by UV\", \"Consider coupling to Fe(III)/Fe(II) redox cycling on iron sulfide minerals\", \"Could invoke wet-dry cycling with atmospheric O\u2082 traces or UV-generated oxidants\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n 